    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Yordan Alvarez** (78.41) and **Trea Turner** (69.16) anchoring the lineup, both benefiting significantly from favorable matchups against soft-throwing opposition. **Yordan Alvarez** boasts an elite .393 xwOBA, and facing Cecconi allows him to leverage that profile into our highest daily efficiency score. Meanwhile, **Trea Turner** remains our primary engine for the scarce stolen base category; despite facing a modest challenge in hold rates from Rea, the combination of a leadoff spot and a 4.36 xERA opponent creates a high-ceiling environment. **Kyle Schwarber** (68.80) rounds out the tier-one offensive threats, thriving against Rea\u2019s 4.36 xERA, while **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (61.34) sneaks into the strong-start category thanks to a massive 14% boost from favorable platoon splits, overcoming the risk posed by Nola\u2019s elite catcher pop time.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Dillon Dingler** (36.01), who flirted with the 40.0 threshold but was ultimately benched due to a significant 15% penalty against right-handed pitching, which neutralized the park and order benefits he otherwise enjoyed against Gray. We are monitoring **Kazuma Okamoto** (43.67) closely, as his status remains listed as \"Lineup Pending.\" While our projection assumes a #7 spot, any downward shift in the order could jeopardize his marginal score, especially against a solid arm in Detmers. Elsewhere, the speed-chasing nature of our roster continues to dictate playing time; **Victor Scott II** (44.94) starts despite a bottom-tier lineup position because his elite sprint speed is a category-maker for our build, even if the current matchup against Meyer suggests a limited output. With **Christian Yelich** and **Zac Veen** unavailable, the bench depth remains thin, reinforcing our reliance on the projected efficiency of our primary nine to avoid burning through our game cap limits.",
